Timeplot:

Let us first generate the timeplot:

retail_series %>%
  autoplot(Turnover) +
  labs(y = "Turnover (million $AUD)", x = "Time (Years)",
       title = retail_series$Industry[1],
       subtitle = retail_series$State[1])

This series clearly shows a non-linear upward trend and a strong seasonal pattern. These seasonal patterns seem proportional to the level of the trend over this time period.

In case it is unclear whether the seasonality follows a yearly pattern, we could further divide the x-graph:

retail_series %>%
  
  autoplot(Turnover) +
  
  labs(y = "Turnover (million $AUD)", x = "Time (Years)",
       title = retail_series$Industry[1],
       subtitle = retail_series$State[1]) + 

  scale_x_yearmonth(date_breaks = "1 year",
                    date_minor_breaks = "1 year") +
  
  # Flip x-labels by 90 degrees
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90))

Just for your knowledge, please note that autoplot function is nothing else but a wrapper for other ggplot functions:

retail_series %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = Month, y = Turnover)) +
  
  geom_line() +
  
  labs(y = "Turnover (million $AUD)", x = "Time (Years)",
     title = retail_series$Industry[1],
     subtitle = retail_series$State[1]) +
  
  scale_x_yearmonth(date_breaks = "1 year",
                    date_minor_breaks = "1 year") +

  # Flip x-labels by 90 degrees
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90))

season plot

retail_series %>%
  gg_season(Turnover, labels = "both") +
  labs(y = "Turnover (million $AUD)",
       title = retail_series$Industry[1],
       subtitle = retail_series$State[1])

  • Large increases in clothing retailing can be observed in December (probably a Christmas effect).
  • Peak in July that appears to be getting stronger over time. 2016 had an unusual pattern in the first half of the year.

Seasonal subseries plots

retail_series %>%
  gg_subseries(Turnover) +
  labs(y = "Turnover (million $AUD)", x="")

  • Growth trend in all months.
  • largest increase in December.
  • July and August also present an above average growth.
retail_series %>%
  
  # Creates the lagplot
  gg_lag(Turnover, lags=1:24, geom='point') + 
  
  # Adjusts the nubmer of columns
  # See source code for .lag:
  # https://rdrr.io/github/tidyverts/tsibblestats/src/R/graphics.R
  facet_wrap(~ .lag, ncol=6)

retail_series %>%
  ACF(Turnover, lag_max = 50) %>%
  autoplot()

Both the lagplot and the correlogram show a much greater correlation with lags 12, 24 This clearly indicates that there is a seasonal pattern of 12 months in this series.

On the other hand, the lagplot exhibits a continuous slowly-decreasing pattern. This indicates that variables close in time are also highly correlated, which is what we expect if the series cointains a clear trend component.

aus_production %>%

The first quarter tends to be the worst in terms of bricks production, and the second or third quarter tend to be the yearly picks.

aus_production %>%

## Warning: Removed 5 row(s) containing missing values (geom_path).

One noteworthy aspect is that the decrease in the last 25 years has been less marked on Q1.

aus_production %>%

aus_production %>%
  ACF(Bricks) %>% autoplot() +
  
  # Flip x-labels by 90 degrees

The spikes in the correlogram on the multiples of 4 indicate that this series exhibits yearly seasonality. This is much clearer on the correlogram than in the lagplots, which might not be so informative in this particular case due to the effect of the trend.

On the other hand the trend is also reflected on the correlogram in the continuous slowly-decreasing pattern. This indicates that nearby observations are also near in value, that is, there is a trend. Note that this remains true even though the trend reverses at one point.

2.2 Snowshoe Hare pelts traded

The pelt dataset (loaded with fpp3) contains trading records for Snowshoe Hare and Canadian Lynx furs from 1845 to 1935. This data contains trade records for all areas of the company. Use ?pelt to obtain further information.

Focus on the series corresponding to the Snowshow Hare

Hare_tr <- pelt %>%
  select(Year, Hare)

# Combines both heads and tails vertically
bind_rows(head(Hare_tr), tail(Hare_tr))
## # A tsibble: 12 x 2 [1Y]
##     Year  Hare

## 10  1933 89760

#NOTE: because we are working with years, stored as double or int
# instead of as a specific date object, it is best to use sequences
# to define the ticks of the axes (if we wish to control them)

# To define their bounds we use the min() and max() function. We extend them
# a bit further because the x axis itself extends a bit further as well.
major_ticks_seq = seq(min(Hare_tr$Year)+5, max(Hare_tr$Year)-5, 5)
minor_ticks_seq = seq(min(Hare_tr$Year)-5, max(Hare_tr$Year)+5, 1)

Hare_tr %>%
  
  autoplot(Hare) +
  
  # I use scale_x_continuous because the variable "Year" is stored as a numeric type
  # instead of a date type.
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = major_ticks_seq,
                     minor_breaks = minor_ticks_seq)

The series exhibits cyclic behavior with great variability in the period length (between roughly five and ten years).

There is a string difference between the peaks of each cycle.

In this case there is no point in depicting the seasonal plot or the seasonal subseries plot because we are dealing with yearly data and therefore there is no seasonality analysis. Remember that seasonal patterns are associated to calendar structures (quarters, months, weeks, days, hours). Therefore if we have yearly data there is no seasonality to be analysed.

Hare_tr %>%
  gg_lag(Hare, geom='point')

Hare_tr %>%
  ACF(Hare) %>% autoplot()

The lagplots themselves do not reveal any particularly obvious corerlation. The correlogram, on the other hand, shows that lags 5 and 10 correspond to the greatest autocorrelation coefficients. None of them is greater than 0.5, but these two lags correspond to the greatest dependencies.

group_by() + n()

Examining the dataset, to filter out costs corresponding to the category ATC2 = h02 and generate data with the monthly expenses corresponding to that grop.

When using group_by(), we can always combine it with summarise() + n() to check the size of each of the groups being formed:

PBS %>%
  filter(ATC2 == "H02") %>%
  group_by(ATC2) %>%
  summarise(
    # Returns the size of each group
    size = n()
  )

We would like to add all those costs together, and that is what the following code does:

h02 <- PBS %>%

  group_by(ATC2, ATC2_desc) %>%
  summarise(Cost = sum(Cost))

ungroup()

Ungrouping: note that, in the above output, there is an indication that the data is still grouped following the variable ATC2. This means that any operations being performed on the data are performed on the grouped data.

As an example, let us try to simply make a sub-selection of Month and Cost on this data:

head(select(h02, Month, Cost))
## Adding missing grouping variables: `ATC2`
## # A tsibble: 6 x 3 [1M]
## # Key:       ATC2 [1]
## # Groups:    ATC2 [1]
##   ATC2     Month   Cost
##   <chr>    <mth>  <dbl>
## 1 H02   1991 Jul 429795
## 2 H02   1991 Aug 400906
## 3 H02   1991 Sep 432159
## 4 H02   1991 Oct 492543
## 5 H02   1991 Nov 502369
## 6 H02   1991 Dec 602652

We observe that the variable ATC2 has been automatically added, despite our intention to drop it in our select statement. The reason is that the data is still grouped using this variable under the hood, and therefore this variable is necessary and cannot be dropped.

If we wish to remove grouping and return to operations on ungrouped data, we need to use the function ungroup()

h02 <- h02 %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  select(Month, Cost)

head(h02)
## # A tsibble: 6 x 2 [1M]
##      Month   Cost
##      <mth>  <dbl>
## 1 1991 Jul 429795
## 2 1991 Aug 400906
## 3 1991 Sep 432159
## 4 1991 Oct 492543
## 5 1991 Nov 502369
## 6 1991 Dec 602652

Now we have been able to drop the variable ATC2.

Analysis

h02 %>%
  autoplot(Cost) +
  
  # We use scale_x_yearmonth() because these are the units of the time index
  scale_x_yearmonth(date_breaks = "1 year",
                    minor_breaks = "1 year") +
  
  # Flip x-labels by 90 degrees
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90))

The graph revels yearly seasonality as well as an upwards trend. Further, the variability in the seasonal pattern seems to be proportional to the level of the trend.

There is as well a noteworthy drop every February.

h02 %>%
  gg_season(Cost)

The graph reveals the underlying upwards trend of the series, as well as the drop occurring every February.

h02 %>%
  gg_subseries(Cost)

This seasonal subseries plot reveals that months with typically higher peaks have experienced a greater growth (greater difference between their lowest and greatest record) than months with lower records.

h02 %>%
  gg_lag(Cost, geom='point', lags=1:16)

h02 %>%
  ACF(Cost) %>% autoplot()

The strong yearly seasonality is clear in the spike of the ACF every 12 lags(). The lagplots show a separate cluster of points in almost every graph that matches the large sales in January.

us_gasoline %>%
  gg_season(Barrels)

The noise makes it difficult to spot the seasonal pattern.

us_gasoline %>%
  gg_subseries(Barrels)

The bluelines mark the average levels in each week of the year. On average, production seems to increase until Q3 to then decrease.

us_gasoline %>%
  gg_lag(Barrels, geom='point')

us_gasoline %>%
  ACF(Barrels, lag_max = 160) %>% autoplot()

In this case, the lagplots are not all that useful because of the big amount of weeks per year. In order to see the seasonal pattern on the correlogram, we need to increase the number of lags at least beyond 52 (number of weeks in a year). If we do this, we clearly observe yearly seasonality.

3.2 Google Stock Prices

The following code computes the daily changes in Google closing stock prices for 2018:

dgoog <- gafa_stock %>%
  
  # Filter data for google and year 2018
  filter(Symbol == "GOOG", year(Date) >= 2018) %>%
  
  # Creates a new index based on the trading day
  mutate(trading_day = row_number()) %>%
  select(Symbol, trading_day, Close) %>%

  # Update the tsibble changing the index to the trading day
  update_tsibble(index = trading_day, regular = TRUE) %>%

  # Compute the difference in closing price
  mutate(diff = difference(Close, lag = 1))

QUESTION: Why is NA - NA = NA? Can you give a mathematical example?

  1. Why was it necessary to create a new index for the tsibble based on the trading day? Hint: run ?update_tsibble on the console to access the documentation and read about the argument regular.

Trading occurs at irregular intervals in time (market days). The new index is based solely on an enumeration of trading days and therefore we could say that it happens at irregular intervals.

  1. Create a time plot of the closing prices and a time plot of the differences.
dgoog %>% autoplot(Close)

dgoog %>% autoplot(diff)

  1. Create the correlogram of the Closing prices and of the differences in prices using the ACF() and autoplot() functions. Depict 100 lags (look at the argument lag_max).
dgoog %>% ACF(Close, lag_max=100) %>% autoplot()

dgoog %>% ACF(diff, lag_max=100) %>% autoplot()

  • Do the differences in the stock prices look like white noise?

More than 95% of the values of the correlogram are within the dashed bounds, so we can consider the differences in the stock prices as white nose
